    <stitle>ANTILOCK RELAY VALVE: AR-1 - BALANCED OR HOLDING</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>BALANCED OR HOLDING</title>
        <svcsubsecinfo>
            <para>The air pressure being delivered to the antilock modulators and brake chambers is also present beneath
                the relay piston (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0402604">Figure 4</hotlnk>
                ). When the air pressure above and below the relay piston is equal, the piston moves slightly, allowing
                the inlet valve to return to its seat. The exhaust valve remains closed. With both the inlet and exhaust
                valves closed, air pressure in the antilock modulators and brake chambers is held stable and neither
                increases nor decreases.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0402604" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0402604" filename="../figg04/G0402604.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. AR 1 Holding Balanced</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1.QUICK EXHAUST DIAPHRAGM</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SERVICE PORT</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. RELAY PISTON</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. INLET/EXHAUST VALVE</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. DELIVERY PORT</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. ANTILOCK MODULATOR</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. BRAKE CHAMBER</callout1>
                    <callout1>8.EXHAUST</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. PRIMARY RESERVOIR</callout1>
                    <callout1>10. SUPPLY PORT</callout1>
                    <callout1>11.EXHAUST</callout1>
                    <callout1>12. ANTILOCK CONTROLLER</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubsecinfo>
    </svcsubsec>
